<div1 type="trialAccount" id="t18561027-1069">
               <interp inst="t18561027-1069" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18561027"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18561027-1069" type="date" value="18561027"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18561027-1069-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-1069-18561027 t18561027-1069-offence-1 t18561027-1069-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>1069. <persName id="def1-1069-18561027" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-1069-18561027" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1069-18561027" type="surname" value="GOWER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1069-18561027" type="given" value="RICHARD"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">RICHARD GOWER</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18561027-1069-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18561027-1069-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18561027-1069-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="embezzlement"></interp> for embezzlement.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MESSRS. BODKIN</hi>. <hi rend="italic">and</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">POLAND</hi>. <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18561027-name-749" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18561027-name-749" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18561027-name-749" type="surname" value="LINN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18561027-name-749" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>HENRY LINN</persName>
                  </hi>. I am ticket collector in the employ of the South Eastern Railway Company, at Forest Hill, the prisoner was head ticket collector there. On 18th Aug., I collected the tickets at the half past 7 o'clock—Margate train—this is the book—I received from passengers who had no tickets 2<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—on the following morning, I paid that to the prisoner, and he signed the book, "Received, Richard Gower"—I saw him sign it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18561027-name-750" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18561027-name-750" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18561027-name-750" type="surname" value="AKERS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18561027-name-750" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM AKERS LORD</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a collector of tickets at Forest Hill, in the employ of the South Eastern Railway Company. On 18th Aug., I col<lb></lb>lected the tickets for the half past 7 o'clock Margate train—I received 2<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 7<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. from passengers who had no tickets—on the following morning I handed that to the prisoner—it is entered here in my book, and he signed it, "Richard Cower"—"No tickets, 2<hi rend="italic">l</hi>."—"No tickets, 7<hi rend="italic">s</hi>."—I handed these together—I have the excess book here—it is the duty of the prisoner to enter the sums he receives from the ticket collectors into this book—in the entry of 18th Aug., these two sums are entered—I entered them myself that day, by the prisoner's directions—the entry is "No tickets, Margate, 2<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 7<hi rend="italic">s</hi>."—I find here an entry of 2<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 17<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—that includes the 2<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>., received from Linn—I copied it by his directions from Linn's book—the total amount that day is 10<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 7<hi rend="italic">d</hi>., including those two sums—this book is kept in counterfoil—the counterfoil is kept in the book—the other part is sent up to London—in this account of 18th Aug., I made the entry in the counterfoil—I showed it to the prisoner after it was made—when the duplicate is made out, it is generally given to the prisoner, but if he had left, it was put under cover for him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> How was it sent? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> It was forwarded by the train, under cover, directed to Mr. Gower, booking office, London Bridge—the duplicate I made out corresponded with the counterfoil.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. LILLEY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> What was done with the counterfoil on 18th Aug.? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> It is here in the book—the duplicate, to the best of my belief, was given to the prisoner, but if he were gone, it was sent to him—I do not remember—my attention was called to this matter on the day the prisoner was given into custody—about 17th or 18th Sept, I copied these in the book by desire of the prisoner—this is the company's book, as well as these smaller books—I do not know how long the prisoner has been in the employ of the company—I have been in the service five years—he was in the service when I came.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Is it his duty to make these entries? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, but I have often done it by his direction—I believe he used to look at it—I cannot say whether he looked at it on this particular night.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18561027-name-751" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18561027-name-751" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18561027-name-751" type="surname" value="CHATWIN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18561027-name-751" type="given" value="FREDERICK"></interp>FREDERICK CHATWIN</persName>
                  </hi>. I am ticket collector of the South Eastern Rail<lb></lb>way, at Forest Hill. On 22nd Aug., I received 4<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. and 15<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. for passengers by the Reigate train, from persons who had not tickets—I paid that sum to the prisoner on the following morning—I have the book here—these sums are entered in the book—the prisoner signed it when I handed him the money—in the excess book of the next day I made out this account, under the direction of the prisoner—in this counterfoil here is this 4<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.1</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="185610270178"></xptr>
               <p>entered by the 9 o'clock Reigate train, persons with no tickets—the gross amount is 3<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 4<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>., that is the amount of the whole day, in addition to writing the counterfoil—I made out the duplicate account, which was sent to London—the duplicate corresponded with the counterfoil exactly—when I made the duplicate, I gave it to the prisoner—I remember that day.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> How often do you copy the account in this book! <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> About once a week—some weeks twice—it depended on whether Lord was there or not—when Lord was not there, I did it—this book was intended as a check for the whole—I copied the duplicate and counterfoil of 22nd Aug.—I have a distinct recollection of handing the sheet over to the prisoner—I never sent any, I always handed them to the prisoner—I know I handed it to him that day—he was on the platform—he lives in Tooley-street—he came down by the quarter past 9 o'clock train in the morning—it was in the evening I handed him this account.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BODKIN</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> What you entered was from the small books into this? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, and it has the prisoner's signature.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18561027-name-752" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18561027-name-752" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18561027-name-752" type="surname" value="MUNRO"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18561027-name-752" type="given" value="DONALD"></interp>DONALD MUNRO</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a clerk in the employ of the Brighton Railway Company. This account (<hi rend="italic">Looking at it</hi>) is my writing—it is for 2<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>., it is the account of Friday, 22nd Aug.—I wrote it out by the wish of Mr. Gower—he came into the office one morning with his right hand tied up—he said he had got his thumb smashed, and would we be kind enough to write a few lines for him—another clerk and I were in the office—I said, "Certainly," and I wrote this from a slip of paper which he produced—he took the slip of paper away with him—I copied this from the paper and from his dictation, both—he held the piece of paper in his hand and read it out to me—the paper was about the same size as one of these duplicates—I did not observe whether there was any printing on the paper he read it from—the account I wrote was written on a regular form, an excess form—the prisoner gave me that form to write it on—in the account I made out I do not see anything like 4<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. for tickets for Reigate—what I made out was 2<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—his right hand was tied up with a handkerchief round it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> The prisoner produced what you call an excess form, and you wrote on it? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—he handed it to me—I did not see the paper from which I copied it—he held it in his hand—I might have looked at it—I cannot tell where the excess papers are deposited—I believed his thumb was injured.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18561027-name-753" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18561027-name-753" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18561027-name-753" type="surname" value="COCKERTON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18561027-name-753" type="given" value="CHRISTOPHER EDWARD"></interp>CHRISTOPHER EDWARD COCKERTON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am station clerk at the London Bridge terminus. I should say the prisoner has been in the employ of the company from ten to twelve years—he has been head ticket collector for four or five years past—of late the up trains stop at Forest Hill, and the tickets are taken there—the prisoner had the superintendence of that station—it was his duty, at the close of the day, to fill up a form, and half was for<lb></lb>warded to the London station—that ought to contain all the money received—this counterfoil of 18th Aug. did not come to me—this duplicate came to me as the duplicate of the excess book of 18th Aug.—the duplicates have come to me from Forest Hill by casual persons, in an envelope, generally—the prisoner did not bring them at all himself, they came by the train—by the paper that came on 18th Aug., the amount represented as received is 3<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 0<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 8<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—in the counterfoil of that date, under the head of Margate, here appears 2<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 17<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. and 2<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 7<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—the account of them has not been rendered to me—in the counterfoil of 22nd Aug., the amount is 3<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 4<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>., and what was sent up to me was 2<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—it reached me in the same way in course of business.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="185610270179"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> The amount of the counterfoil of 22nd Aug. is 3<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 4<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>., and the paper you received 2<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—I am not quite certain when it was discovered that this variance existed—it was about 2nd or 3rd Sept—after this alleged fraud had been discovered, Mr. White, an accountant, came to me, and the prisoner was with him—Mr. White asked him what was the amount which had been rendered by him to the company—it was then found that the counterfoils and the accounts did not agree.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Are you sure as to the time that the prisoner has been in the service of the company, is it not as long as thirteen years? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I have been there twelve years—I think he was there when I came—during the last three months I have occasionally received gross sums on account—on 18th Aug. I did not receive a sum from him—he left it with another person—on 22nd Aug. I received 15<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., and there was still a small balance left in his hands—I know that he received the money in small sums from the ticket collectors—the excess forms are always sent up in an envelope—I find them in the letter box, or they are brought in by some of the guards—I have known him some years—I always thought him an honest man.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BODKIN</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Was that 15<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. on account of moneys he had received? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—I had no open account with him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18561027-name-754" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18561027-name-754" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18561027-name-754" type="surname" value="WHITE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18561027-name-754" type="given" value="DAVID"></interp>DAVID WHITE</persName>
                  </hi>. I am an accountant in the employ of the Railway Com<lb></lb>pany. I was sent down to Forest Hill station—I saw the prisoner there—I asked him to give me an account of the discrepancies there were between the counterfoils and the money paid—he said he did not understand it—I showed him the duplicates—he gave me no explanation—he came up to London with me—I took him, first of all, to the booking office, to see Mr. Cockerton, and after that to the general manager's office—the matter was then stated in presence of the prisoner—he was again asked for an expla<lb></lb>nation—we could get nothing more out of him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> What was the answer he gave? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> "I do not un<lb></lb>derstand you"—I asked him for an explanation—he replied, "I do not un<lb></lb>derstand it"—I pointed out to him the difference between the counterfoil and the returns, and that was what he said at both offices—he came readily with me, and brought the books with him—I went down on a special mission.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BODKIN</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did you show him this document of 18th Aug? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> That was the one I called his attention to—the difference between that and the counterfoil—I asked him whose writing the duplicate was, he said he did not know—he did not say that was not the return he made.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18561027-name-755" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18561027-name-755" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18561027-name-755" type="surname" value="DUFF"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18561027-name-755" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>HENRY DUFF</persName>
                  </hi>. (<hi rend="italic">policeman, M</hi> 219). On 3rd Sept, I took the prisoner into custody—I told him he was charged with embezzling 2<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 17<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>., on 18th Aug.—he made no reply to the charge—when at the station he gave me 15<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. in gold—one gold coin, 2<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 0<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 10<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. in silver, and 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 2 1/2 <hi rend="italic">d</hi>. in copper—while I was counting it, he said, "I dare say you think it strange that I have got so much money in my pocket, but some of that money belongs to the South Eastern Railway Company," mentioning the name of some person which I did not hear.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Where did you take him? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> At the London Bridge station, I think in one of the directors' offices—he did not say he wanted to pay this money over—he did not say he was ready to pay it over—he said, "I dare say you think it strange that I have got so much money, but some of it belongs to the South Eastern Railway."</p>
               <p>(<hi rend="italic">The prisoner received a good character.</hi>)</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <rs id="t18561027-1069-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
                        <interp inst="t18561027-1069-verdict-1" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18561027-1069-verdict-1" type="verdictSubcategory" value="no_subcategory"></interp>GUILTY</rs>
                  </hi>.—<hi rend="italic">
                     <rs id="t18561027-1069-punishment-132" type="punishmentDescription">
                        <interp inst="t18561027-1069-punishment-132" type="punishmentCategory" value="imprison"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18561027-1069-punishment-132" type="punishmentSubcategory" value="penalServitude"></interp>
                        <join result="defendantPunishment" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-1069-18561027 t18561027-1069-punishment-132"></join>Four Years Penal Servitude.</rs>
                  </hi>
               </p>
               <p>(<hi rend="italic">The whole amount of the prisoner's embezzlement was stated to be about</hi> 200<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.)</p>
            </div1>
